File: Ginger is rich in antioxidants and has medicinal benefits. Unsplash/sentot setyasiswanto JOHANNESBURG - Pick n Pay has agreed to cap its gross profit margin for ginger and garlic. This follows an agreement with the competition commission after recent public complaints against several retailers for price gouging.
Pick n Pay is the first retailer to sign the agreement. READ: Competition Commission to probe garlic, ginger prices The retailer will cap its profits in the period covering January 28 to April, the first this year and could extend it further. In terms of the Consumer Protection Regulations, ginger and garlic fall under the category of basic food and consumer items.